<paragraph id="8B9336CE003EFFEEFF6CFA80FDE1584C" blockId="8.[151,1437,1405,2043]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">
<bibRefCitation id="EFBD4B3F003EFFEEFF6CFA80FE415ADB" author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[151,435,1405,1431]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" pagination="575 - 579" refId="ref6317" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (1992) Generos de Hemilophini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Lamiinae) com antenas de doze articulos. Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 36 (3), 575 - 579." type="journal article" year="1992">Martins &amp; Galileo (1992)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFDD0FA83FD255ADB" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="1992" box="[555,727,1405,1431]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFDD0FA83FD255ADB" box="[555,727,1405,1431]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Juninia beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on a single female from 
<collectingCountry id="F33B765E003EFFEEFBCBFA80FB5B5ADB" box="[1072,1193,1405,1431]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="49E8F82C003EFFEEFB4CFA80FAE45ADB" box="[1207,1302,1405,1431]" country="Costa Rica" name="Cartago" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Cartago</collectingRegion>
). According to them (translated): “The separation of the males of the species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFC74FA5FFC1A5AF7" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" box="[911,1000,1442,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Purusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFC74FA5FFC1A5AF7" box="[911,1000,1442,1467]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Purusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFBDBFA5FFB865AF7" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1966" box="[1056,1140,1442,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFBDBFA5FFB865AF7" box="[1056,1140,1442,1467]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Juninia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is immediate: the frons in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFF6CFA3BFF025A93" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" box="[151,240,1478,1503]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Purusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFF6CFA3BFF025A93" box="[151,240,1478,1503]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Purusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is strongly projected and in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFDDCFA3BFD895A93" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1966" box="[551,635,1478,1503]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFDDCFA3BFD895A93" box="[551,635,1478,1503]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Juninia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
regularly convex, without projections. Since the frontal projections, that occur in several genera of this tribe, are a secondary sexual character, the distinction between females of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFAB3FA17FA6E594F" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1966" box="[1352,1436,1514,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFAB3FA17FA6E594F" box="[1352,1436,1514,1539]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Juninia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFF3DF9F3FEED596B" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" box="[198,287,1550,1575]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Purusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFF3DF9F3FEED596B" box="[198,287,1550,1575]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Purusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is still difficult. We do not know females of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFCEAF9F3FC9C596B" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1966" box="[785,878,1549,1575]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leechi">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFCEAF9F3FC9C596B" box="[785,878,1549,1575]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">J. leechi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but we have a female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFB75F9F3FAF7596B" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" box="[1166,1285,1550,1575]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Purusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acreana">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFB75F9F3FAF7596B" box="[1166,1285,1550,1575]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">P. acreana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in our hands. The shape of the elytral apex and the color pattern led us to describe 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFC5EF9CFFBE05907" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="1992" box="[933,1042,1585,1611]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFC5EF9CFFBE05907" box="[933,1042,1585,1611]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">J. beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFBC3F9CFFB7E5907" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1966" box="[1080,1164,1586,1611]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFBC3F9CFFB7E5907" box="[1080,1164,1586,1611]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Juninia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.” When they received a male of the species, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBD4B3F003EFFEEFE78F9A8FD5A5923" author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[387,680,1621,1647]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" pagination="109 - 116" refId="ref6365" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (1993) Descricao de novos taxons com antenas de doze articulos, transferencia de especies de Adesmus Lepeletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1825 e sinonimos (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Lamiinae, Hemilophini). Iheringia, Zoologia, 74, 109 - 116." type="journal article" year="1993">Martins &amp; Galileo (1993)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFCDDF9A8FC465923" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="1993" box="[806,948,1621,1647]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sibapipunga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFCDDF9A8FC465923" box="[806,948,1621,1647]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Sibapipunga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to include 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFBCCF9ABFB145923" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="1992" box="[1079,1254,1621,1647]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFBCCF9ABFB145923" box="[1079,1254,1621,1647]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Juninia beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has two large tubercles on frons. In the description of the genus, they only noted that the humeral carina is prolonged to the apical quarter. As seeing before, according to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBD4B3F003EFFEEFD6DF960FC4559FB" author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[662,951,1693,1719]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" pagination="1868" refId="ref6425" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (2014) Subfamilia Lamiinae, Hemilophini Thomson, 1868. Parte I. In: Martins, U. R. (Org.), Cerambycidae Sul-Americanos (Coleoptera). Volume 13. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Curitiba, pp. 3 - 231." type="book chapter" year="2014">Martins &amp; Galileo (2014)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFC39F960FBA259FB" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="1993" box="[962,1104,1693,1719]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sibapipunga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFC39F960FBA259FB" box="[962,1104,1693,1719]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Sibapipunga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would have only the humeral carina, lacking another lateral carina. However, although very close to the humeral carina, there is a second carina in male (
<figureCitation id="13172A4B003EFFEEFF01F918FEB959B3" box="[250,331,1765,1791]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–26" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1920,1944]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,382,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-136@6.[151,1436,381,1897]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 21–26. Sibapipunga beckeri (Martins &amp; Galileo, 1992). 21) Holotype female, dorsal habitus. 22–25) Male: 22) Dorsal habitus; 23) Ventral habitus; 24) Lateral habitus; 25) Frontal tubercles. 26) Holotype female, elytral carinae (by Diego de Santana Souza)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6581646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6581646/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
) and female (26).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3366545003EFFEFFF3CF8F4FD615801" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="160" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9336CE003EFFEEFF3CF8F4FEB9580B" blockId="8.[151,1437,1405,2043]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">
<bibRefCitation id="EFBD4B3F003EFFEEFF3CF8F4FE19586F" author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[199,491,1801,1827]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" pagination="109 - 116" refId="ref6365" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (1993) Descricao de novos taxons com antenas de doze articulos, transferencia de especies de Adesmus Lepeletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1825 e sinonimos (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Lamiinae, Hemilophini). Iheringia, Zoologia, 74, 109 - 116." type="journal article" year="1993">Martins &amp; Galileo (1993)</bibRefCitation>
recorded 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFDA4F8F4FD3D586F" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="1992" box="[607,719,1801,1827]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFDA4F8F4FD3D586F" box="[607,719,1801,1827]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">S. beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for 
<collectingCountry id="F33B765E003EFFEEFCFAF8F4FCAC586F" box="[769,862,1801,1827]" name="Ecuador" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
and Martins &amp; Galileo (2004) examined a female from 
<collectingCountry id="F33B765E003EFFEEFF2EF8D0FEB5580B" box="[213,327,1837,1863]" name="Colombia" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Colombia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9336CE003EFFEEFF3CF8ACFAE158C3" blockId="8.[151,1437,1405,2043]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">
In the male of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003EFFEEFE95F8ACFE2F5827" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="1992" box="[366,477,1873,1899]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003EFFEEFE95F8ACFE2F5827" box="[366,477,1873,1899]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">S. beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the humeri are distinctly projected, while they are not so in female, the outer apical angles of the elytra are distinctly more projected than in the female, and the antennae are much longer.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9336CE003EFFEEFF3CF864FC3C58B7" blockId="8.[151,1437,1405,2043]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">
The tarsal claws in the female (
<figureCitation id="13172A4B003EFFEEFDDEF864FD8458FF" box="[549,630,1945,1971]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–32" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1847,1871]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,1137,1822]" captionTargetId="figure-420@7.[151,1436,1137,1823]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 27–32. Protarsal claws. 27–28) Sibapipunga beckeri (Martins &amp; Galileo, 1992): 27) Holotype female (by Diego de Santana Souza); 28) Male. 29–30) Purusia acreana Lane, 1956: 29) Holotype male; 30) Female. 31–32) Juninia annulifera (Kirsch, 1889): 31) Female; 32) Juninia leechi Lane, 1966, paratype male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6581648" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6581648/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) and male (
<figureCitation id="13172A4B003EFFEEFD00F864FCBE58FF" box="[763,844,1945,1971]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–32" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1847,1871]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,1137,1822]" captionTargetId="figure-420@7.[151,1436,1137,1823]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 27–32. Protarsal claws. 27–28) Sibapipunga beckeri (Martins &amp; Galileo, 1992): 27) Holotype female (by Diego de Santana Souza); 28) Male. 29–30) Purusia acreana Lane, 1956: 29) Holotype male; 30) Female. 31–32) Juninia annulifera (Kirsch, 1889): 31) Female; 32) Juninia leechi Lane, 1966, paratype male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6581648" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6581648/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
) are similar, with the inner tooth noticeably widened basally. However, the inner tooth in the male is considerably shorter than in the female.As we had only one pair, we do not know if the length of the inner tooth is variable between the sexes.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF536646003FFFEFFF6CF9C4FB3C5939" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6581650" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6581650" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6581650/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" startId="9.[151,264,1593,1617]" targetBox="[151,1436,193,1569]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph id="8B9336CE003FFFEFFF6CF9C4FB3C5939" blockId="9.[151,1436,1593,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003FFFEFFF6CF9C4FEA1591D" bold="true" box="[151,339,1593,1617]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">FIGURES 33–38.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C2C4D4D003FFFEFFEA3F9C7FE1B591D" authority="Heffern &amp; Santos-Silva, 2022" authorityName="Heffern &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2022" box="[344,489,1593,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="raberi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B958EADC003FFFEFFEA3F9C7FE1B591D" box="[344,489,1593,1617]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Juninia raberi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B958EADC003FFFEFFE14F9C4FD7E591D" bold="true" box="[495,652,1593,1617]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A26B57A7003FFFEFFE14F9C4FDCC591D" box="[495,574,1593,1617]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
33–37)
</emphasis>
Holotype female: 
<emphasis id="B958EADC003FFFEFFCBDF9C4FC9A591D" bold="true" box="[838,872,1593,1617]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">33)</emphasis>
Dorsal habitus; 
<emphasis id="B958EADC003FFFEFFBF7F9C4FBDC591D" bold="true" box="[1036,1070,1593,1617]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">34)</emphasis>
Ventral habitus; 
<emphasis id="B958EADC003FFFEFFB23F9C4FB0B591D" bold="true" box="[1240,1273,1593,1617]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">35)</emphasis>
Lateral habitus; 
<emphasis id="B958EADC003FFFEFFF6CF9A0FF4B5939" bold="true" box="[151,185,1629,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">36)</emphasis>
Elytral carinae; 
<emphasis id="B958EADC003FFFEFFE9AF9A0FE715939" bold="true" box="[353,387,1629,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">37)</emphasis>
Head, frontal view. 
<emphasis id="B958EADC003FFFEFFDAAF9A0FD815939" bold="true" box="[593,627,1629,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">38)</emphasis>
Paratype female, dorsal habitus (by Armando Ruiz Boyer).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B9336CE003FFFEFFF3CF95EFB6A59F2" blockId="9.[151,1436,1699,1870]" box="[199,1176,1699,1726]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
